"The one-page tune-from-here sheet. Every arcade game starts by
picking numbers for gravity, mass, friction, drag, and speed cap.
This appendix suggests values that WORK, catalogued by game type.

## world/gravity!

`world/gravity! x y` sets world acceleration in pixels/frame^2.

| Game type              | (world/gravity! x y)       | Feel               |
|------------------------|----------------------------|--------------------|
| Falling-ball demo      | (world/gravity! 0 0.5)     | Playground ball    |
| Slow-fall for aesthetic| (world/gravity! 0 0.15)    | Slow-mo, dreamy    |
| Fast-fall for tension  | (world/gravity! 0 0.9)     | Snappy, brutal     |
| Platformer default     | (world/gravity! 0 0.6)     | Standard jump      |
| Floaty platformer      | (world/gravity! 0 0.35)    | Cosmic feel        |
| Heavy platformer       | (world/gravity! 0 0.85)    | Weight, thump      |
| Space (no gravity)     | (world/gravity! 0 0)       | Frictionless drift |
| Space with attractor   | (world/gravity! 0 0)       | + world/attract!   |
| Tilted-corner rainfall | (world/gravity! 0.2 0.5)   | Sideways drift     |
| Anti-gravity (helium)  | (world/gravity! 0 -0.3)    | Balls float up     |

Rule of thumb: for a game that PRESSURES the player, gravity 0.5-0.7.
For a game that gives them TIME to react, gravity 0.3-0.4.

## entity/mass!

`entity/mass! ent m` sets mass. Default is 1. Mass affects momentum
transfer during collision. It does NOT affect fall speed in a
frictionless world (Galileo).

| Purpose                | (entity/mass! e m)   | Effect                    |
|------------------------|----------------------|---------------------------|
| Default ball           | (entity/mass! b 1)   | Standard behavior         |
| Heavy immovable target | (entity/mass! e 100) | Player pushes weakly      |
| Light bullet           | (entity/mass! b 0.1) | Doesn't disturb hits      |
| Boulder                | (entity/mass! r 5)   | Rolls with real weight    |
| Feather                | (entity/mass! f 0.3) | Wafts, easily deflected   |
| Immovable wall         | (entity/mass! w 999) | Nothing pushes it         |

## entity/friction!

`entity/friction! ent f` sets floor drag. 0 = frictionless surface;
1 = infinite friction (sticks). Actually not that binary in practice.

| Surface           | (entity/friction! e f) |
|-------------------|------------------------|
| Ice               | (entity/friction! e 0.01) |
| Wood floor        | (entity/friction! e 0.05) |
| Carpet            | (entity/friction! e 0.15) |
| Gravel            | (entity/friction! e 0.25) |
| Mud               | (entity/friction! e 0.45) |
| Molasses / glue   | (entity/friction! e 0.75) |

Ice level: friction 0.01, player slides. Grass level: friction 0.15,
player stops normally. Molasses level: friction 0.75, player crawls.
Design levels around friction as much as around geometry.

## entity/drag!

`entity/drag! ent d` sets air drag. Different from friction (which
is floor-based). Drag applies to velocity through the air.

| Purpose                | (entity/drag! e d)  | Effect             |
|------------------------|---------------------|--------------------|
| Space (no drag)        | (entity/drag! e 0)  | Coasts forever     |
| Water (heavy drag)     | (entity/drag! e 0.05)| Slows in air       |
| Underwater             | (entity/drag! e 0.15)| Very slow motion   |
| Normal air             | (entity/drag! e 0.01)| Subtle slowdown    |

For a game where the player must feel WEIGHT of decision, small drag
gives every input importance. In space games use 0.

## entity/max-speed!

`entity/max-speed! ent v` caps velocity. Prevents runaway speeds.

| Purpose             | (entity/max-speed! e v) |
|---------------------|------------------------|
| Player character    | (entity/max-speed! p 4) |
| Fast-runner powerup | (entity/max-speed! p 8) |
| Slow enemy          | (entity/max-speed! e 1) |
| Fast enemy          | (entity/max-speed! e 3) |
| Bullet              | (entity/max-speed! b 8) |
| Boss                | (entity/max-speed! b 2) |

Rule: max-speed of enemies should be < player. Otherwise no escape.
Max-speed of bullets should be > player to guarantee player must dodge.

## entity/gravity-scale!

`entity/gravity-scale! ent k` multiplies world gravity for one entity.

| Purpose                 | (entity/gravity-scale! e k) |
|-------------------------|-----------------------------|
| Default                 | (entity/gravity-scale! e 1)  |
| Bird (light)            | (entity/gravity-scale! e 0.3)|
| Heavy character         | (entity/gravity-scale! e 1.5)|
| Anti-grav               | (entity/gravity-scale! e -1) |
| Jump apex hang          | (entity/gravity-scale! e 0.5) |
| Fast fall               | (entity/gravity-scale! e 1.3) |

The chapter-7 jump uses this variably: 0.7 while rising, 0.4 near
apex, 1.2 while falling.

## The kit — starter values by game type

**Platformer starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0.6)
(entity/mass! player 1)
(entity/friction! player 0.1)
(entity/max-speed! player 4)
(entity/bounce! player 0)
```

**Space shooter starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0)
(entity/mass! ship 1)
(entity/drag! ship 0.01)
(entity/max-speed! ship 5)
```

**Physics puzzle starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0.5)
(entity/friction! box 0.2)
(entity/mass! box 3)
(entity/bounce! box 0.15)
```

**Pinball starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0.4)
(entity/mass! ball 1)
(entity/bounce! ball 0.9)
(entity/friction! ball 0.03)
(entity/max-speed! ball 12)
```

**Racing starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0)   ; top-down
(entity/drag! car 0.03)
(entity/mass! car 2)
(entity/max-speed! car 8)
```

**Falling-object avoid starter:**
```
(world/gravity! 0 0.3)
(entity/gravity-scale! player 0)  ; player doesn't fall
(entity/mass! debris 1)
(entity/bounce! debris 0.2)
```

## Combining constants — the interaction matrix

Some constant pairs conflict:
- High bounce + high friction: ball bounces in place, wastes energy
  horizontally. Fix: correlate them inversely.
- Zero drag + high gravity: entities accelerate to unplayable speeds
  in seconds. Fix: add max-speed cap.
- Zero gravity + high mass: mass doesn't matter (no weight force).
  Fine — mass then only affects collision transfer.
- High gravity-scale + solid enemy: enemy accelerates into ground
  hard, bounces or squashes. Test.

## Playtest cadence

Set your constants. Play for 30 seconds. Change ONE value by ±20%.
Play again. If it's better, keep. If worse, revert. Repeat until
each knob is at its best-of-30-tests value.

Never change two knobs at once. You lose the ability to attribute
change.

## The 12-line tune loop

Here's a live-tune workbench for a bouncing ball:

```scheme
(define g 0.5)
(define b 0.85)
(define f 0.05)
(define (tune-ball)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 g)
  (world/floor! 240)
  (let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 160 20)))
    (entity/bounce! ball b)
    (entity/friction! ball f)
    (entity/shape! ball 'circle 6)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/pressed? 'up)   (set! g (+ g 0.05)))
       (when (input/pressed? 'down) (set! g (- g 0.05)))
       (when (input/pressed? 'left) (set! b (- b 0.05)))
       (when (input/pressed? 'right)(set! b (+ b 0.05)))
       (world/gravity! 0 g)
       (entity/bounce! ball b)
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x ball) (entity/y ball) 6 6)
       (paint-text (string-append \"g:\" (number->string g)
                                  \" b:\" (number->string b)) 10 10)))))
(big-bang tune-ball)
```

That is the closed-loop tune. Every physics decision in the book
comes down to numbers from this sheet.")
